lusive.\nThe Pennsylvania Railroad maintains a comprehensive\nschedule of fosl express trains to Chicago, St. Louis, Indi\nanpolis. Louisville, Columbus, Cleveland, and Toledo ftom\nthe principal cities of the East.\nFull details of the reduced fare arrangements for these\nconventions and the through western train service may he\nobtained of any Pennsylvania Railroad Ticket Agent.\nMiss Annie Jackson has taken her\nplace at the Chapel school.\nMr, Arthur Bryde ha* returned to\nWashington after spending the put\nmonth at his home here.\nMr. and Mrs. George Thompson, of\nWest Nottingham, and Mr. and Mrs.\nHarvey Kntter and children, erf Perry\nville, spent Sunday with Mr. and Mri.\nJ. T. Rutter.\nMr. Edwin Barnes spent the week\nend with his family in Wilmington.\nMrs. George Rutter, of Baltimore,\nspent thin week with Mrs. John T.\nRutter,\nZION.\n\nChildren's Hay services will be held\nin the Presbyterian Church, Sunday\nmorning, June 7.\nMrs. Emma Mearns is visiting\nfriends in Wilmington and Philadel\nphia.\nMrs. Eva Collier, of Rising Sun, is\na guest at the home of Mr. and Mrs.\nEdwin Carhart.\nThe 'Helping Hand\" was entertain\ned at the home of Mrs. Margaret Cro\nthers on Friday evening.\nMiss Anna Wright and nephey, Mr.\nHarry Martindale, Jr., of New York,\nare the guests of Mr. and Mrs. Charles\nMorris.\nRev. and Mrs J B. Brinkcma were\nPhiladelphia visitors on Monday.\nMr and Mrs. Kelson Warner, of\nWilmington, were the week-end guests\nof Mr. and Mrs. Henry Warner.\nMr George McVey is visiting\nfriends in Baltimore.\nMiss Lidia Churchman, of Sylmar,\nlias been a recent visitor ot the home\nof Mr William Perry.\nThe members of the Presbyterian\nChurch will hold a festival on the\nChurch lawn, Wednesday evening,\nMay 27.\nMr. and Mrs William Cameron and\nchildren spent Sunday with Mr. and\nMrs Arthur Cameron, of Lincoln.\nMiss Anna Mary Crolhers, of\nGreenlmrst, was an over Sunday guest\nat the home of Mr. William Lynch.\nFor Union Hospital\nJ in- Ladies' Au